      <h2>How to Use the Side Hustle Calculator</h2>
      <p>Whether you are freelancing, driving for a rideshare service, selling products online, or doing consulting work on the side, understanding your actual take-home pay is essential for making informed financial decisions. This calculator breaks down the often-surprising tax implications of self-employment income so you can see exactly what you keep from every dollar earned.</p>

      <p>Start by entering your total annual gross revenue from your side hustle. This is the full amount clients or customers pay you before any deductions. Next, enter your annual business expenses, which include everything from software subscriptions and supplies to home office costs and mileage. The difference between revenue and expenses is your net profit, which forms the basis for all tax calculations.</p>

      <p>Enter your estimated marginal income tax rate. If you have a regular W-2 job, your side hustle income is taxed on top of that income, so use the tax bracket that applies to your combined income. Common rates are 12%, 22%, or 24% depending on your total income level and filing status. Finally, enter the average number of hours per week you spend on your side hustle to calculate your effective hourly rate.</p>

      <p>The calculator computes self-employment tax using the IRS formula: 92.35% of your net profit multiplied by 15.3%. This covers both the employee and employer portions of Social Security (12.4%) and Medicare (2.9%) taxes. Unlike W-2 employees who split FICA with their employer, self-employed individuals pay the full amount. The calculator then estimates income tax on your net profit and subtracts both tax amounts to show your true take-home pay.</p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Self-Employment Tax</h2>
      <p>The self-employment tax is often the biggest surprise for new freelancers and side hustlers. At 15.3% of 92.35% of net earnings, it adds a significant tax burden on top of regular income tax. The 92.35% factor exists because the IRS allows self-employed individuals to deduct the employer-equivalent portion of FICA, mirroring what W-2 employees receive. You can also deduct half of your self-employment tax when calculating your adjusted gross income, though this calculator uses the simplified approach for estimation purposes.</p>

      <h3>Maximizing Your Side Hustle Income</h3>
      <p>Track every legitimate business expense meticulously, as each deduction directly reduces both your income tax and self-employment tax. Consider setting up a dedicated business bank account and credit card to simplify record keeping. Set aside 25-30% of your gross revenue for taxes in a separate savings account so you are prepared for quarterly estimated payments. Evaluate whether your effective hourly rate justifies the time investment, and consider raising prices if it does not.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How much self-employment tax do I owe on side hustle income?</h3>
      <p>Self-employment tax is 15.3% of 92.35% of your net self-employment income, covering Social Security (12.4%) and Medicare (2.9%). For example, if your net profit is $40,000, your SE tax would be approximately $5,652.</p>

      <h3>What business expenses can I deduct from my side hustle?</h3>
      <p>Common deductible expenses include home office costs, equipment and supplies, software subscriptions, internet and phone bills (business portion), vehicle mileage, advertising, professional services, and continuing education.</p>

      <h3>Do I need to pay quarterly estimated taxes on side hustle income?</h3>
      <p>If you expect to owe $1,000 or more in taxes for the year, the IRS requires quarterly estimated tax payments. Failing to make estimated payments can result in underpayment penalties.</p>

      <h3>How do I calculate my effective hourly rate from a side hustle?</h3>
      <p>Divide your annual take-home pay (after all taxes) by the total hours you work per year. This gives a realistic picture of what your time is actually worth after taxes and expenses.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between gross revenue and net profit for a side hustle?</h3>
      <p>Gross revenue is the total amount you earn before deductions. Net profit is what remains after subtracting all business expenses. Net profit is the amount subject to self-employment tax and income tax.</p>


